        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We observe 13CO line at SPW1, 29SiO line at SPW2, and CO, AlO, and AlOH lines at SPW3, respectively. We also observe continuum simultaneously with these lines using the off-line spectra of the three SPWs to estimate its contribution to the flux. To lower the data rate, we average SPW1 and SPW2 to make the spectral resolution 0.85 km/s. Individual lines are within the effective bandwidths. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The silicate dust formation and consequent depletion of SiO molecule is expected to occur at 2 stellar radii (0.036 arcsec) from the star (Norris et al., 2012). In order to observe the SiO and CO line fluxes inside and outside the silicate forming region, we require the angular resolution of 0.036 arcsec. Silicate formation should cease within 5 stellar radii and thus we require the largest angular scale of 0.18 arcsec (10 stellar radii).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>  In order to estimate the sensitivity, we evaluate the line fluxes of CO and ^{29}SiO based on the two-dimensional simulation of gas lines in the envelope of W Hya and the CASA simulator, of which details are as follows.

Simulation
  We made two-dimensional simulation of CO and SiO emissions in the envelope of W Hya. The stellar radius (R_{star}) of 3.4 x 10^{13} cm and the distance of 98 pc were adopted (Vlemmings et al. 2003, 2011). The envelope was assumed to be spherical in the model. The inner edge of the dust shell (R_{cond}) was set at 2 R_{star} (Norris et al., 2012). The random velocity of 5 km/s was assumed for the gas inside R_{cond}, while the terminal expansion velocity of 8.1 km/s with the random motion of 5 km/s for the gas beyond R_{cond} (Knapp et al. 1998). The mass-loss rate was set at 1.7 x 10^{-7} M_{Sun}/yr (Knapp et al. 1998). The density profile of SiO was given by decreasing a certain fraction at R_{cond} from that scaled to the CO density profile with the cosmic SiO/CO ratio to simulate the depletion of SiO due to silicate formation. We set the outer edge of the SiO envelope at 200 Rstar (Gonzalez Delgado et al. 2003). W Hya is known to have a clumpy shell structure, and thus the shell with clump structures in the size of 0.1 arcsec was assumed in the simulation (e.g., Reid and Menten 1990, 2007). Similar clumps were also observed in the shell around Mira (ALMA Science Verification Data). For the modeled map of CO and SiO emissions, we simulated observation image taken with the ALMA extended configuration (C36-7) by the CASA simulator. With the typical size of the clump of  ~0.1 arcsec, the clumpy shell can be observed with the ALMA extended configuration (C36-7) without resolving out. 

Sensitivity
  We determine whether or not SiO is depleted beyond the silicate-forming region by comparing the brightness of SiO lines close to the star (&lt;0.05 arcsec) and at ~0.18 arcsec from the star, which is farther than the silicate condensation line (Norris et al. 2012). The fluxes of the 29SiO and 13CO lines at 0.18 arcsec (10 stellar radii) from the star are estimated to be 30 and 13 mJy/beam, respectively (Fig. 3, Table 1). We require the sensitivity to observe the 29SiO line at 0.18 arcsec from the star with 5-sigma confidence even in the case that 70% of SiO condenses as silicates contrary to the expectation that 90% of the SiO remains in the gas phase. 

Bandwidths
We set three spectral windows that cover five lines (29SiO, CO, 13CO, AlO, and AlOH). The line width is estimated from the terminal expansion velocity to be 8.1 km/s., and the spectral resolution of &lt;0.9 km/s is required for all lines. The continuum is also evaluated to evaluate its contribution to the observed flux using the off-line spectra within the three spectral windows (Table 1).  
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
